# Article Structure and Formatting

## Required frontmatter

Every article must have these fields:

```yaml
---
title: Human-Readable Article Title
excerpt: One-sentence description of what the article covers.
meta: SEO-focused description (defaults to excerpt if omitted, but always provide it).
categories:
- Category Name
---
```

- `excerpt`: Brief, user-focused. Describes what the reader will learn or do.
- `meta`: Can differ from excerpt — optimized for search engines and AI answer engines. Include relevant keywords naturally. Write it as a direct answer to the question the article addresses (AI engines pull from meta descriptions when generating citations).
- `categories`: Must match entries in `priorities/categories.yaml`.
- `social` (optional): Path to an image for the `og:image` meta tag (displayed when the URL is shared on social media). Place images in `images/social/`. If omitted, defaults to the `illustration` image if one exists.

## Standard page skeleton

```markdown
---
title: Article Title
excerpt: Brief description.
meta: SEO description.
categories:
- Category Name
---

# Article Title

### Table of Contents {#toc}

* TOC
{:toc}

---

Opening 1–2 sentences: what this page helps the reader do or understand.

## First section {#anchor}

Content...

## Have more questions?

If you have any questions about [topic], [contact support](https://dnsimple.com/feedback), and we'll be happy to help.
```

## Formatting rules

### Headings

- `# H1` = article title (matches frontmatter `title`). Only one per article.
- `## H2` = major sections. Add `{#anchor-name}` for deep linking.
- `### H3` = subsections within an H2.
- Never skip levels (no H4 right after H2).

### Section anchors

Add `{#anchor-name}` to every H2: `## Adding CAA records {#add}`

Use lowercase, hyphenated, short names. These are used in cross-links from other articles.

**Exceptions — do not add anchors to these boilerplate H2s:**

- `## Have more questions?` — closing CTA section; never deep-linked.
- `## Before starting` — introductory prerequisites section; never deep-linked.

These headings have auto-generated slugs that are sufficient. Adding an explicit anchor that matches the auto-slug (e.g. `{#have-more-questions}`) causes kramdown to produce doubled fragment IDs like `#have-more-questions-have-more-questions`.

### Table of contents

Include after the H1 title in articles with 3+ sections:

```markdown
### Table of Contents {#toc}

* TOC
{:toc}

---
```

### Step-by-step instructions

Wrap numbered procedures in the section-steps div:

```markdown
<div class="section-steps" markdown="1">
##### Descriptive heading for this procedure

1. Log into DNSimple with your user credentials.
1. If you have more than one account, select the relevant one.
1. On the header, click the <label>Domains</label> tab...
</div>
```

- Use `1.` for every step (Markdown auto-numbers).
- Use `<label>Label Text</label>` for UI element names.
- Keep steps atomic — one action per step.

### Callouts

Use GitHub-flavored callout syntax. Three types only:

- `[!NOTE]` — things users should be aware of (non-destructive)
- `[!TIP]` — helpful recommendations (non-critical)
- `[!WARNING]` — critical info about permanent or damaging actions

```markdown
> [!NOTE]
> Content here. Each line starts with `>`.
```

Place callouts near the relevant content, not at the end. Use sparingly.

### Lists

Always place a blank line between a colon and the list that follows:

```markdown
The certificate covers:

- Root domain
- Single-level subdomains
```

### Links

- Internal articles: `/articles/article-slug/`
- Developer docs: `https://developer.dnsimple.com/v2/...`
- Product pages: `https://dnsimple.com/...`
- Link text should describe the destination: `[SSL certificate types](/articles/ssl-certificates-types/)` not `[click here](/articles/ssl-certificates-types/)`

### Images

Place in `/files/` and use descriptive alt text:

```markdown
![SSL certificate page](/files/ssl-certificate-page.png)
```

## SEO and GEO (Generative Engine Optimization)

Articles should be optimized for both traditional search engines and AI answer engines (ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google AI Overviews). These two goals mostly reinforce each other.

### Opening paragraph as extractable answer

The first 1–3 sentences after the H1 should directly answer the core question the article addresses. AI engines use this as their primary citation source. Keep it under 80 words.

- Good: "CAA records let you specify which Certificate Authorities are allowed to issue SSL certificates for your domain. If CAA records are present and the CA is not authorized, the certificate request will be denied."
- Bad: "In this guide, we'll walk you through everything you need to know about CAA records and how they relate to SSL certificates."

### Headings as query targets

Use headings that match how people ask questions — both in search bars and in AI prompts. Question-format H2s for Explanation/Reference articles, imperative-format for How-to articles. Avoid vague headings like "Overview" or "Additional Information."

Each H2 section should be self-contained enough that an AI engine could extract it as a standalone answer.

### Specific claims over vague statements

AI engines prefer content with concrete, citable facts. Include specifics wherever possible.

- Good: "Sectigo certificates are valid for a maximum of 200 days."
- Bad: "Sectigo certificates have a limited validity period."

### Keyword and query coverage

- Place the strongest keywords in the H1 and H2 headings.
- Include natural-language variations of key terms — people ask AI assistants in full sentences, not keyword fragments. Think "How do I renew an SSL certificate in DNSimple?" not just "renew SSL certificate."
- Use the `excerpt` for user-facing summaries and `meta` for search/AI-facing descriptions. Both should contain the primary keyword.

## Category YAML

When creating a new article, add it to the appropriate category YAML file in `categories/`. Articles not listed in a YAML file are grouped under "Other."

- Files are named by category slug: `categories/ssl_certificates.yaml`, `categories/dns.yaml`, etc.
- Top-level keys are Diataxis-aligned sections: `Getting started`, `Explanation`, `How-to`, `Reference`
- Sections can have sub-groups: `Explanation: Certificate Concepts: [...]`
- Articles are listed by their **frontmatter title** (not filename)
- Category display order is controlled by `priorities/categories.yaml`

Example entry — adding a new Explanation article:

```yaml
Explanation:
  Certificate Concepts:
    - "What is a Certificate Authority?"
    - "Understanding SSL Private Keys"   # ← new article
```

## URL changes and redirects

If you rename an article file or change its slug, add a redirect so old URLs still work.

- Redirects are defined in the `_redirects` file in the project root (Netlify format)
- Format: `old-path  new-path` (one per line, spaces between)
- Add the redirect in the same PR as the rename

```
/articles/ordering-standard-certificate/    /articles/ordering-sectigo-certificate/
```

Also search all articles for internal links pointing to the old URL and update them.

## Diataxis type alignment

Before writing, decide the article type and stay within its scope:

| Type | Purpose | Verb mood | Scope |
|---|---|---|---|
| Getting Started | Onboarding | Imperative | Minimal viable path for new users |
| Tutorial | Learning | Imperative | Guided walkthrough with one clear outcome |
| How-to | Task completion | Imperative | Steps to achieve a specific goal |
| Explanation | Understanding | Declarative | Why something works the way it does |
| Reference | Information lookup | Declarative | Specs, tables, lists — no narrative |
